			<ns0:name>mark.d...@gmail.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/117634658684698531165/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">NaCl applications are able set the direction flag in the EFLAGS register
(using std), causing movs and scan instructions to operate in reverse
rather than going forward in memory. Since the EFLAGS register is preserved
across &amp;quot;system calls&amp;quot;, an attacker may set the direction flag and then
request a service from the NaCl runtime and cause memory corruption.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2009-04-10T21:41:44.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2009-03-12T07:30:27.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
